Step 1: Apply the exponent rules to each fraction: $\left( \frac{4}{x} \right)^{-1} = \frac{x}{4},\left( \frac{3x^3}{x} \right)^2 = \frac{9x^6}{x^2}, \left( \frac{1}{2x} \right)^{-3} = \frac{8x^3}{1}$
Step 2: Multiply the fractions together: $\frac{x}{4} \left( \frac{9x^6}{x^2} \right) \left( \frac{8x^3}{1} \right) = \frac{x(9x^6)(8x^3)}{4(x^2)(1)}$
Multiply the numerators and denominators: $\frac{x(9x^6)(8x^3)}{4(x^2)(1)} = \frac{9x^6(8x^3)(x)}{4(x^2)}$
Simplify the numerator and denominator: $\frac{9x^6(8x^3)(x)}{4(x^2)} = \frac{72x^9}{4(x^2)}$
Divide the numerator and denominator by their greatest common factor: $\frac{72x^9}{4(x^2)} = \frac{18x^7}{1}$
Simplify the expression: $\frac{18x^7}{1}=18x^7$
